Enumeration

Port 8080: HTTP

There is an image gallery web application on this port. However, I do not have the credentials for this application. While performing some directory search, I tested the different default credentials but I did not have any luck.


However, I bypassed the authentication mechanism when I tested the inputs for SQL injection with the payload admin' OR '1'='1' -- //. This application is vulnerable to SQL injection.

Exploitation


Gaining a shell is pretty simple. The web application allows file upload. I uploaded a PHP Pentest Monkey reverse shell with the name shell.php. I started a listener on port 8443, and pressed the three dots on the image, and then the Download button to start the connection. Now I have a foothold on the target machine.

Privilege Escalation


The initialize.php contains juicy information as shown above. The credential gallery_user:passw0rd321 is a SQL login.


Using the credential, I gained access to the MySQL application. The password hash of user admin exists.



After manual enumeration, I finally obtained the password of the user mike. This user made a backup at /var/backups/. There I can access the .bash_history which contains the commands this user has entered. This file contains the password b3stpassw0rdbr0xx.


And now I evelated my privileges to the user mike on the target machine.


Running sudo -l shows the interesting command above.


Gaining a root shell is pretty simple. Running cat /opt/rootkit.sh shows the read command uses nano. And I used the command reset; sh 1>&0 2>&0 to spawn a root shell. Before I did this, I made the terminal stable.
